I see, thanks.

> Hoping you didn't start work on this already

No indeed, thanks for doing it :)

> Maybe this is a use case for having the hwy::Abort function interface well defined and stable, and allowing defining one within a project if you want different abort behaviour? I'm not sure it's worth adding all the functionality to dynamically set it given the only use-case is NumPy.

Dynamic setting functionality seems very doable and potentially beneficial.
It could be as simple as:

```
typedef void (*AbortFunc)(const char* file, int line, const char* formatted_err);

AbortFunc& GetAbortFunc() {
	static AbortFunc func;
	return func;
}

// When func is called, and does not intend to terminate the program, it must
// also call the return value of this function.
AbortFunc SetAbortFunc(AbortFunc func) {
	const AbortFunc prev = GetAbortFunc();
	GetAbortFunc() = func;
	return prev;
}
```

Returning the previous function would allow callers to see if someone else has already set one, or also pre-abort 'hooks' enabled by each AbortFunc calling the previous one from their registration.
If GetAbortFunc is null, or the function (chain) still hasn't exited, we resume with the current implementation.
